{
  "answer": "**In the Yājñavalkya Smṛti (Chapter 3, verse 40), no specific penance (prāyaścitta) is prescribed.**[^1]\n\nInstead, the verse prohibits the sale of lac, salt, and meat (even for a Brahmin in distress adopting a Vaiśya occupation), while stating that selling milk, curd, or liquor results in demotion to a lower *varṇa*.[^2] This falls under the section on duties in times of distress (*āpaddharmaprakaraṇam*), emphasizing occupational restrictions rather than expiatory rites.\n\n[^1]: Yājñavalkya Smṛti, Chapter 3, [paragraph](/works/unknown-yajnavalkya-smrti-cb88d6/03/translation/#p-6d9cb4).\n[^2]: Yājñavalkya Smṛti, Chapter 3, [paragraphs](/works/unknown-yajnavalkya-smrti-cb88d6/03/translation/#p-a9755d_p-6d9cb4_p-c03f6a).",
